Man he is really going to do   the funniest trade in the whole history of f=
inancial markets:

Adam Neumann and capital providers including Dan Loeb=E2=80=99s Third Point=
 are exploring an offer to buy WeWork Inc. out of bankruptcy, according to =
a letter sent to WeWork=E2=80=99s lawyers that was seen by Bloomberg News.
Neumann and Third Point have been trying to get information from WeWork nec=
essary to formulate a bid since December, according to the letter. More rec=
ently they=E2=80=99ve worked to put together a bankruptcy financing package=
 for the co-working firm.
The bid would be for the entire company or its assets, according to the let=
ter. It did not include details of how much Neumann, who co-founded WeWork,=
 stood ready to offer for the firm.
Currently, WeWork=E2=80=99s bankruptcy plan proposes handing ownership to t=
he company=E2=80=99s most senior debt holders, including those holding its =
credit line, first-lien notes and second-lien notes, according to court pap=
ers. Third-lien noteholders and unsecured creditors are likely to be wiped =
out.

Here is  the letter, from  Dealbook. The short version of this trade is tha=
t Adam Neumann started WeWork, sold it to SoftBank Group Corp. head Masayos=
hi Son=C2=A0for $47 billion in one of the greatest=20
feats of salesmanship ever, left, watched it collapse, and will now buy it =
back for $0. The slightly longer version is:
=09Adam Neumann started WeWork and raised billions of dollars to expand, la=
rgely from SoftBank,=C2=A0at equity valuations=C2=A0as high as $47 billion;=
 he also took out roughly $1.7 billion for himself in stock sales and   non=
-recourse loans.=09WeWork filed for bankruptcy in November, its=C2=A0curren=
t equity value is $0, and SoftBank has torched its multibillion-dollar inve=
stment.=09But Neumann still has=C2=A0his=C2=A0money, and he clearly misses =
WeWork. (He currently keeps busy with   a startup called Flow, a sort of re=
sidential-real-estate clone of WeWork, with social events and a lot of tech=
-company blather.)=09WeWork is now on sale for $0, and Neumann might buy it=
.=09Then he could take Masayoshi Son out for lunch and be like =E2=80=9Ctha=
t was fun, let=E2=80=99s do it again sometime=E2=80=9D and leave Son with t=
he check.

The actual numbers are not quite as good as that. WeWork=E2=80=99s equity i=
s worthless, but it has a lot of debt, and buying it out of bankruptcy woul=
d presumably require paying off at least some of that debt. But the current=
 bankruptcy plan actually does=C2=A0not involve paying off any of the debt:=
 Holders of WeWork=E2=80=99s roughly $3.7 billion of first- and second-lien=
 debt would swap their debt into equity and own the surviving company, whil=
e the third-lien, unsecured and stock would get nothing.
  [1]
=C2=A0(SoftBank, in addition to its now-worthless equity, also owns a chunk=
 of the debt.)
Presumably to compete with that =E2=80=94=C2=A0and to own the company himse=
lf, rather than giving it to the lenders =E2=80=94=C2=A0he would need to of=
fer the lenders something better. Maybe that would mean paying off the most=
 senior debt in full (so like $4 billion), or maybe it would mean giving th=
em some cash plus some ownership in the surviving company, while getting th=
e rest for himself. Neumann can=E2=80=99t actually acquire WeWork for $0 in=
 cash, which is why he is working with capital providers.
  [2]
=C2=A0And =E2=80=9Csome experts have suggested that WeWork could be sold fo=
r a fraction of its outstanding debt, perhaps for as little as $500 million=
,=E2=80=9D  reports Dealbook, so the bid/ask could be wide and it could be =
hard to get a deal done. Also SoftBank is one of the lenders and there migh=
t be hard feelings there.=C2=A0Still, Adam Neumann has gotten a lot of hila=
rious deals done in his life; maybe he=E2=80=99ll pull this one off.
And, just, what a great trade. Here are three fairly conventional things yo=
u could say about WeWork:
=09As a business idea it seems fine? You rent big chunks of office building=
s for long periods, you divide them up, you provide nice desks and common a=
reas and happy hours, and you rent them in smaller chunks for shorter time =
periods to customers, at a premium to your cost. This seems like a particul=
arly good idea now, as companies navigate a new world of flexible working a=
rrangements: Managing flexible workspace is a valuable service for companie=
s, and WeWork seems well positioned to provide it.=09On the other hand, in =
a world of flexible work, the absolute demand for office space is lower tha=
n it used to be, so WeWork probably has too many long-term leases on too mu=
ch space, and is paying too much for them.
  [3]
 Fortunately   bankruptcy gives WeWork flexibility to cancel leases it does=
n=E2=80=99t need, and leverage to renegotiate others!=09WeWork=E2=80=99s bi=
g problem is not that it was a bad idea but that it grew insanely fast, add=
ing new space faster than it could fill the old space and leaving it partic=
ularly vulnerable to a downturn. This was good for raising money from SoftB=
ank at a $47 billion valuation, because SoftBank prioritized growth and amb=
ition above everything else. But it incinerated a lot of value and was bad =
for WeWork=E2=80=99s ability to survive. But, again, bankruptcy fixes that:=
 WeWork can cut its debt, get rid of leases it doesn=E2=80=99t want, and en=
d up at a rational size for its business model.

We have   talked   around   here about what I call the Wag trade. Wag Labs =
Inc. is a dog-walking startup that raised $300 million from SoftBank at a $=
650 million valuation in 2018. A dog-walking startup! Three hundred million=
 dollars! It didn=E2=80=99t even want that much =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was tryin=
g to raise $75 million =E2=80=94 but SoftBank, loving growth and ambition, =
insisted that it take $300 million to expand rapidly. And then, a year late=
r, when that had not worked out, Wag bought back SoftBank=E2=80=99s stake a=
t a discount.   I wrote:

Wag was looking to raise $75 million. It went to SoftBank and was like =E2=
=80=9Cwill you give us $75 million?=E2=80=9D SoftBank was like =E2=80=9Cno =
haha we=E2=80=99ll give you $300 million,=E2=80=9D because that is SoftBank=
=E2=80=99s whole thing, it loves to give startups vastly more money than th=
ey want or need. And so Wag took the money. And then like a year and a half=
 later Wag will get rid of SoftBank by giving back, I don=E2=80=99t know, b=
ut I am going to say some number less than $225 million (=E2=80=9Cwell belo=
w=E2=80=9D the valuation at which it invested). Wag got the $75 million it =
needed=C2=A0for free.
The trade, to be clear, is: If you need a little bit of money to grow your =
business modestly, you can raise a lot of money from SoftBank to grow your =
business crazily, and then put most of it in the bank and use a little bit =
of it to grow modestly instead. SoftBank will be disappointed with the mode=
st growth, and you can say =E2=80=9Csorry it didn=E2=80=99t work out=E2=80=
=9D and then buy them out at a lower valuation with the money you have left=
 over from not growing your business crazily. Free (modest) growth capital!

That is clearly not what WeWork did. WeWork took a lot of money from SoftBa=
nk to grow its business crazily, and really did that, and it worked out ter=
ribly, and WeWork was left with nothing in the bank.
But Adam Neumann wasn=E2=80=99t there for most of that run; he was enjoying=
 his mansions and doing Flow for the worst parts of WeWork=E2=80=99s collap=
se. And if you just=C2=A0ignore, you know, 2017 through 2023, and focus on =
Neumann=E2=80=99s personal balance sheet, you get roughly the Wag trade:=C2=
=A0
=09Neumann had a smallish, growing, exciting real estate company.=09SoftBan=
k gave him something like $1.7 billion for himself.=09Events occurred.=09He=
 might end up with roughly that same smallish exciting real estate company,=
 now with more reasonable expenses, plus he=E2=80=99ll probably keep a lot =
of the $1.7 billion.

Surely=C2=A0SoftBank=C2=A0wishes that none of it had ever happened, but for=
 Neumann, I mean,   could be worse. He=E2=80=99s probably richer than he wo=
uld have been without SoftBank. In some ways this has not been great for hi=
s reputation, but in other ways it has been amazing=C2=A0for his reputation=
? You have to respect a good trade, and   Neumann=E2=80=99s timing is impec=
cable. He found the top of the startup bubble, he found (in Masayoshi Son) =
the best possible person to sell overhyped startup stock to, and he sold So=
n a pile of overhyped startup stock so he could become a billionaire. But b=
uried within Neumann=E2=80=99s overhyped startup stock, and his amazing pat=
ter about being =E2=80=9Cthe world=E2=80=99s first physical social network=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ca state of consciousness,=E2=80=9D was =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0a perfectly fine little real estate company? That was the prop that he n=
eeded to extract billions of dollars out of Son. But now it has done its jo=
b, and Neumann would like the real estate company back. It=E2=80=99s not li=
ke SoftBank needs it anymore.

