<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The actual numbers are not <em>quite </em>as g=
ood as that. WeWork=E2=80=99s equity is worthless, but it has a lot of debt=
, and buying it out of bankruptcy would presumably require paying off at le=
ast some of that debt. But the current bankruptcy plan actually does=C2=A0<=
em>not </em>involve paying off any of the debt: Holders of WeWork=E2=80=99s=
 roughly $3.7 billion of first- and second-lien debt would swap their debt =
into equity and own the surviving company, while the third-lien, unsecured =
and stock would get nothing.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0(SoftBank, in addition to its now-worthless equity, also owns a c=
hunk of the debt.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Presumably to compete with that =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and to own the company himself, rather than giving it to the lenders =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0he would need to offer the lenders something better. Maybe that=
 would mean paying off the most senior debt in full (so like $4 billion), o=
r maybe it would mean giving them some cash plus some ownership in the surv=
iving company, while getting the rest for himself. Neumann can=E2=80=99t ac=
tually acquire WeWork for $0 in cash, which is why he is working with capit=
al providers.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And =E2=80=9Csome experts have suggested that WeWork could be sol=
d for a fraction of its outstanding debt, perhaps for as little as $500 mil=
lion,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/342=
57326.257392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyNC8wMi8wNi9idXNpbmVzcy9kZW=
FsYm9vay9uZXVtYW5uLXdld29yay10YWtlb3Zlci5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC1b0=
8ac49" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> reports Dealbook</a>, so the bid/ask could be wide and it c=
ould be hard to get a deal done. Also SoftBank is one of the lenders and th=
ere might be hard feelings there.=C2=A0Still, Adam Neumann has gotten a lot=
 of hilarious deals done in his life; maybe he=E2=80=99ll pull this one off=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, just, what a great trade. Here are three =
fairly conventional things you could say about WeWork:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">As a business idea it seems fine? You=
 rent big chunks of office buildings for long periods, you divide them up, =
you provide nice desks and common areas and happy hours, and you rent them =
in smaller chunks for shorter time periods to customers, at a premium to yo=
ur cost. This seems like a <em>particularly </em>good idea <em>now</em>, as=
 companies navigate a new world of flexible working arrangements: Managing =
flexible workspace is a valuable service for companies, and WeWork seems we=
ll positioned to provide it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">On th=
e other hand, in a world of flexible work, the absolute demand for office s=
pace is lower than it used to be, so WeWork probably has too many long-term=
 leases on too much space, and is paying too much for them.<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> Fortunately <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
4257326.257392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMt=
MTEtMDcvd2V3b3JrLXMtYmFua3J1cHRjeS1jYXBzLXN3aWZ0LWRvd25mYWxsLWZvci00Ny1iaWx=
saW9uLXN0YW5kb3V0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMDYyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haW=
wmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDIwNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZ=
XlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCfe158b57" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  bankruptcy gives WeW=
ork flexibility</a> to cancel leases it doesn=E2=80=99t need, and leverage =
to renegotiate others!</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">WeWork=E2=
=80=99s big problem is not that it was a bad idea but that it grew insanely=
 fast, adding new space faster than it could fill the old space and leaving=
 it particularly vulnerable to a downturn. This was good for raising money =
from SoftBank at a $47 billion valuation, because SoftBank prioritized grow=
th and ambition above everything else. But it incinerated a lot of value an=
d was bad for WeWork=E2=80=99s ability to survive. But, again, bankruptcy f=
ixes that: WeWork can cut its debt, get rid of leases it doesn=E2=80=99t wa=
nt, and end up at a rational size for its business model.</li>
</ol>
