<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">The basis trade</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Periodically people worry about =E2=80=9Cthe b=
asis trade,=E2=80=9D usually meaning the trade in which:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Hedge funds buy a lot of Treasury bon=
ds, putting up very little of their own money and using mostly money borrow=
ed in the repo markets, and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Those =
hedge funds sell a lot of Treasury futures, putting down very little of the=
ir own money as margin.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Treasury bonds are supposed to be very safe, a=
nd the two legs of this trade mostly offset each other, which means that th=
e trade can be very leveraged, which means that if something goes wrong it =
goes very wrong, which means, like, Danger Lurking in the Safest Asset, so =
it=E2=80=99s an exciting=C2=A0thing to worry about.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But why=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>there a basis tr=
ade? Somebody is buying Treasury futures from hedge funds: Why? Why aren=E2=
=80=99t those people just buying Treasury bonds directly? Why do hedge fund=
s=C2=A0need to sit between the US Treasury (which sells Treasury bonds) and=
 whoever wants Treasury exposure? Why do futures trade at a premium to cash=
 Treasuries? Why do the hedge funds make money? Why is this trade a trade?<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/34257326.257392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMTQvcGVvcGxlLWFyZS13b3JyaWVkLWFib3V0LXRoZS1iYXNpcy10c=
mFkZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjA2MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3Vy=
Y2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAyMDYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb78913fd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> tried to answer those questions la=
st September</a>, basically pointing to long-term asset managers=C2=A0who (=
1) want=C2=A0<em>credit=C2=A0</em>exposure, so they don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0own =
Treasuries (they own corporate bonds or other things with credit risk) but =
(2) also want=C2=A0<em>duration=C2=A0</em>exposure, and most credit product=
 has less duration than long-term Treasuries. So asset managers invest thei=
r actual cash in corporate bonds, and then add duration through futures, an=
d hedge funds get paid to provide them that duration.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not a perfect explanation =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0why is there a basis trade in fairly short-dated Treasuries? =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but it seems to be=C2=A0roughly right.=C2=A0Last week the Treasury Bo=
rrowing Advisory Committee released a =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34257326.257392/aHR0cHM6Ly9ob21lLnRyZWFzdXJ5Lm=
dvdi9zeXN0ZW0vZmlsZXMvMjIxL1RCQUNDaGFyZ2UxUTEyMDI0LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB37c9dc19" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">Discussion of Treasury Futures Positions Across Di=
fferent Investor Types</a>,=E2=80=9D trying to explain the basis trade. Ale=
xandra Scaggs <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3425=
7326.257392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZjA2NDZlY2MtZTI2YS00MmVjLWJ=
mYmYtMDA3YzIwMzFjOWU2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa47d8ab5" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote abou=
t it at FT Alphaville</a>; here=E2=80=99s her summary:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Remember that rates were very low in the pre-2=
022 world. So asset managers who wanted to juice their fund=E2=80=99s yield=
 often kept larger allocations to credit than existed in the benchmark (oft=
en the Bloomberg US Agg). But credit has shorter duration by design, meanin=
g it doesn=E2=80=99t carry as much interest rate risk as the benchmark for =
most funds. So instead of changing the fund=E2=80=99s entire strategy, a ma=
nager could maintain his or her duration exposure by taking leveraged Treas=
ury positions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In theory, this leverage could come from futur=
es or repo markets, but the cost of repo trades are reported as interest ex=
pense, unlike repo futures markets. The TBAC presentation suggests that dis=
suades fund managers from pursuing that leverage in repo markets.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An asset manager who wants to have 100% of her=
 assets in credit, and who also wants to have the same duration as the benc=
hmark, could in theory just put 100% in credit <em>plus</em>=C2=A020% (or w=
hatever) in long-dated cash Treasuries, and borrow money (in the repo marke=
t) to buy the extra 20%. But there are reasons not to do that: reporting re=
po as interest expense, but also regulatory reasons. Traditional asset mana=
gers tend to be nervous about getting leverage by <em>borrowing money</em>,=
 whereas getting leverage in <em>futures markets=C2=A0</em>is more acceptab=
le. The TBAC report notes that =E2=80=9Cfor many years prior to 2020, the a=
pplicable rules created incentives for mutual funds to favor derivatives li=
ke futures over repo in certain cases, including limitations on the size of=
 repo borrowing=E2=80=9D; those rules have been relaxed recently, but =E2=
=80=9Cin our view, many mutual funds are still limiting the size of their r=
epo borrowing and achieving leverage through futures.=E2=80=9D And so inste=
ad of borrowing from repo markets themselves, asset managers effectively bo=
rrow from the futures markets; hedge funds borrow from the repo market, len=
d in the futures market, and collect a spread for their trouble.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way, the numbers in the previous paragr=
aph are=C2=A0fake, but you can get more realistic numbers on page 16 of <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34257326.257392/aHR0c=
HM6Ly9ob21lLnRyZWFzdXJ5Lmdvdi9zeXN0ZW0vZmlsZXMvMjIxL1RCQUNDaGFyZ2UxUTEyMDI0=
LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC37c9dc19" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the TBAC report</a>. =E2=
=80=9CPresently, the Agg is about 42% Treasuries, and in total, about 80% g=
overnment risk.=E2=80=9D But=C2=A0the credit component of the index has=C2=
=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>duration than the Treasuries component: The average d=
uration of Treasuries in the index is 6.15, versus=C2=A07.10 for investment=
-grade corporate bonds. So the story is not quite =E2=80=9Casset managers w=
ant to be overexposed to credit, which has shorter duration than Treasuries=
, so they get their duration from futures.=E2=80=9D It is more that asset m=
anagers want to be overexposed to=C2=A0credit, which has=C2=A0<em>different=
=C2=A0</em>duration from the Treasuries in the index, so they=C2=A0<em>adju=
st=C2=A0</em>their duration exposure using futures. From the report:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Spread sector investment decisions are made in=
 assets of varying durations and maturities, and are often thought of separ=
ately from interest rate investment decisions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Although asset managers have different investm=
ent approaches, we believe it=E2=80=99s common to separate decisions made o=
n interest rate duration and credit spread duration.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Futures allow asset managers to make credit al=
location decisions relatively seamlessly, without impacting interest rate r=
isk exposures, but can introduce basis risk between the futures allocation =
and the Treasury allocation in the index. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s likely that structural overweight=
 positions in credit products could result in persistently higher allocatio=
ns to Treasury futures amongst asset managers.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere in, loosely, the basis trade: =E2=80=
=9CHedge funds and proprietary trading firms that regularly trade US Treasu=
ries are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34257326.=
257392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMDYv=
